  "original_title": "\u0b9c\u0bc2\u0ba9\u0bcd 9 \u0bae\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0bb0\u0bc2.320 \u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bbf\u0baf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bae\u0bcd",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "320 million lost due to June 9 power outage",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The Sri Lanka Public Utilities Commission has recommended that an investigation be conducted into the power outage, which has cost Rs 320 million as a result of the union action taken by Sri Lanka Electricity Board engineers on June 9.",
        "This has been pointed out in the letter written by the Commission to the Minister of Power and Energy, Kanchana Wijesekhara.",
        "While the hydro power plants could have been operated on the specified day, the commission said that the cost of running the fuel generated power plants was Rs 320 million.",
        "The letter indicated that the electricity board failed to supply electricity from 4.30 am to 8.45 am on June 9 due to the stoppage of water production due to unplanned action.",
        "The commission also accused the Electricity Board of failing to operate the Vimalasurendra, Kanyon, Old Lakshabana, New Lakshabana, Polpitiya, Upper Kothmalai, Victoria, Ranthenikala, Ranthembe, Ukkuvela, and Powathenna power plants within the allotted time.",
        "It has been mentioned in the letter that due to the operationalization of Kalanithissa and Yugadanavi power plants during the said period, their operation has cost 320 million."
      ],
